    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary mb-4">Global Health Inequality: Spending vs Life Expectancy</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-700 max-w-2xl mb-6">
      This EDA project investigates the relationship between global health expenditures and life expectancy across countries using World Bank data. It highlights inequality, efficiency, and visualizes health justice through storytelling.
    </p>

    <div class="prose prose-primary max-w-4xl">
      <h2>üåç Project Overview</h2>
      <p>
        Why do some countries achieve high life expectancy with modest budgets, while others spend massively with little to show? This project explores this question using <strong>health spending data</strong> and <strong>life expectancy</strong> metrics across 1995‚Äì2014.
      </p>

      <h2>üì¶ Data Sources & Structure</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>World Bank: Health Expenditure (per capita, PPP-adjusted, % of GDP)</li>
        <li>World Bank: Life Expectancy at Birth (years)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>We reshaped yearly data into long format and merged by ISO3 country codes.</p>

      <h2>üìà Long-Term Trends</h2>
      <p>Both health spending and life expectancy have risen globally, but inequality in investment far exceeds inequality in outcomes.</p>
      <img src="/images/life_expectancy_over_time.png" alt="Life Expectancy Over Time" class="rounded shadow-md my-6" />
      <p>Ethiopia (ETH) shows the steepest improvement, climbing from ~47 to ~65 years‚Äîa gain of nearly 18 years in two decades. Nigeria (NGA), despite spending more per capita on health, lags behind, rising from ~46 to only ~54 years. More spending does not guarantee better outcomes. Ethiopia‚Äôs success likely stems from effective public health programs, foreign aid utilization, and rapid improvements in maternal/child care.</p>
      <p>India (IND) and China (CHN) show steady, moderate gains. China's leap‚Äîfrom ~70 to ~76 years‚Äîtracks with rising healthcare investment and economic growth. Turkey (TUR) and Brazil (BRA) climb from low- to mid-70s, closely mirroring each other. Both show consistent upward trajectories and effective health reform during the 2000s.</p>
      <p>Japan (JPN) leads the chart, consistently above 83 years, reinforcing its global reputation for longevity. Norway (NOR) and Germany (DEU) follow closely, with life expectancies around 81‚Äì82 years. The United States (USA) remains below its peers‚Äîhovering around 78‚Äì79 years‚Äîdespite the highest per-capita health spending globally.
         This underperformance may highlight systemic inefficiencies, such as unequal access to care, chronic disease burden, and lack of universal insurance. It may also show that lifestyle differences take part.
      </p>
      <img src="/images/gini_over_time.png" alt="Gini Coefficients Over Time" class="rounded shadow-md my-6" />
      
      <h2>üåÄ Inequality Snapshot (2014)</h2>
